Writers aren’t born under some special star. We started without knowing everything, and managed not to stop. The answer to most questions about an idea or how to become a certain type of writer is to get on the horse. 

A trick from the pros: find a mind game to trick your stupid brain into shutting up so you can write. Light a magic candle. Decide this is an experiment you don’t have to show anyone. Write the Most Terrible Version. Imagine a time traveler told you Helen Mirren will win an Oscar for playing the murderer. Pretend you’re Aaron Sorkin.

Hi! It's official. YOU will return for a 5th season. 

It is rare and precious when a TV show gets to tell its complete story as intended. It only happens with genuinely massive support from viewers. Thank you for watching and telling your friends and supporting the show. We love you to death. ❤️🔨

#YOUNetflix #YouSeason5 #comingsoon

The other YOU news is that @mffiii and @hellojustinw will be showrunning the 5th season. 🌟

They’ve been with the show for eons - Justin since season 2, Mike since we were a Lifetime show working out of a small windowless office. They are fantastic writers and producers who are also lovely, kind people. Couldn’t be prouder, not that I can take much credit for anything except being smart to hire them in the first place. 

I’m still with the show as an exec producer, by the way. But they get the big office with the private bathroom,  wall-sized shark aquarium and inter-dimensional portal in the bookcase. 

So: good news day. ❤️❤️🥂

Here’s a picket line selfie and some signs. I can’t tell you how much I’d rather be doing my job and getting my steps in the old fashioned way, by walking the dog to procrastinate. 

One thing the world is about to learn about Hollywood writers is that we are really fucking stubborn when we need to be. 

#wgastrong

Listen, no one wants this strike. Writers would like to get back to work and we’re concerned for our shows’ crews and support staff. 

That said, a small note from the picket line: I didn’t anticipate the joy of being around so many artists again. 

We’ve been siloed apart on long productions, and the pandemic has meant years of remote rooms and self-taped auditions and virtual meetings. I think a big reason the picket lines are thrumming with so much energy is simply that it’s exciting to see one another again. And it feels pretty good to walk alongside people you love and admire and want to fight for. ❤️

#wgastrong #wgastrike

Never had so many lovely, personal messages in one day as I just did from people who listened to this week’s @podcrushed episode. 

Especially from women who experienced pressure to underplay their intellect and creativity growing up — damage that’s stayed with them. I’m not being glib when I promise you (whatever your gender — being a girl is but one common reason a person gets slapped down hard by the patriarchy): it’s not too late to own your superpowers and let other people stew in their discomfort if that’s their self-made boring hell of choice. You have creating to do and a fabulous life to lead. And the world really needs your gifts. I mean, look at this place. Good god. PLEASE just go for it. 

In conclusion, go team and also @pennbadgley @nnnava @scribbledbysophie are a force for good in the world. Xoxoxo ❤️💪🏼✨

By the time we were teenaged girls, we'd all been force-fed the same poison: we'd been told we shouldn't be angry. Warned not to be angry. Told we weren't, in fact, angry. Assured we had nothing to be angry about. 

That's a big reason you were so scared of us -- you could sense that something was being denied, repressed, and that might make us dangerous. Sublimation is a tricky business. Sometimes we'd sense it in ourselves: so much power somewhere inside, that we weren't allowed to explore, that we couldn't even name, much less use.

But then, once in a while. someone would come along. She would scream the truth. And that would split us open with recognition. 

She'd get in trouble. For being angry. (That, too, was a validation.) She wouldn't have an easy life. 

I hope she also knew how many girls she helped.

Flights of angels, Truthteller. ❤️

About 30,000 people follow this account and I figure at least one of you needs to know that Letters to a Young Poet is not about poetry.  it’s not just for poets, or even mostly for poets. Forget poetry. It’s a life book - it’s one of those books that says important things in a way that makes them land in your cells where you need them. 

It’s about things like criticism, conformity, hating your job, how to think about solitude, how to do love, and how to survive grief. 

So if you didn’t know now you know. I’m partial to the Stephen Mitchell translation. Xo

I keep accidentally having all these epiphanies about art and what’s important as this strike goes on. When I say them out loud they sound like silly no-brainers. It’s less about discovering new truth than actually feeling what’s already true. You know? 

Societies rarely get it right with their treatment of artists. But oh man am I glad to be one, walking through a world like this one. 🌻

A long time ago, probs before you were born, I met a guy at @esalen. He was dating a friend and I was having a fling with a dancer from San Francisco, so we became Just Friends. That went on for years, but we weren’t what I’d call good friends — it was always weird. 

Then one night i drank an emboldening amount of sake and kissed him in the sushi restaurant parking lot. Suddenly things weren’t weird anymore whatsoever. 

We got married on the equinox so this is our moon anniversary. Equinoxes are a fabulous time to embark on a love experiment because they are a moment that is perfectly equal. In case you needed an excuse to split a bottle of sake and finally kiss. Kanpai ❤️

HOW TO HAVE A GREAT IDEA FOR A SHORT STORY// 

1. Break an entire feature, one hour pilot, or novel. 
2. Write the outline. 
3. Sit down to actually start writing it. 
4. While you are instead cleaning your bathroom/ organizing your closet/ googling dog rescue volunteering opportunities, randomly think of a lil fun-sized candy of a story idea that is much, much shorter, lighter and easier than the thing you’re supposed to start. 
5. Since it doesn’t count, write it fast and loose in a maximum of two sittings. 
6. Do please tag me in your Pushcart Prize announcement.

Being an artist feels weird to me lately. But I keep thinking of something I was told once that's stuck with me.

To paraphrase: making art is not beside the point and it's not a waste. It is a tiny yet non-futile act in the face of the impossible complexity and horror of the world. Not instead other action; it's a yes-and. The act of creating is how you defy destruction.

GOOD MORNING RROM THE CHAIRWOMAN OF THE REJECTION SOCIETY//

One more near-miss for 2023. Y’all, so many this year. This manuscript. A pile of poems. A gorgeous script I supervised. Ideas I lobbed at friends. The ambitious dinner i oversalted. The short fiction that made the long list. The other chapbook that made the short list. The day I almost convinced my husband that he needed a dachshund immediately. The script I turned in 2 weeks before the strike. The vintage McQueen that’s a teeny bit too small. The book that won’t be finished by the 31st. The weird door in the Airbnb that (post 2 cocktails and 1 afternoon reading about parallel dimensions under a redwood tree) I was low-key certain was a portal that turned out to be an undisclosed laundry room with a foozball table. 

This is really why I’m on instagram, btw. To tell whoever is working hard and needs to hear it that you’re not doing it wrong, it’s only that you never graduate from rejection, not even when your career is going so well you can buy yourself a ridiculously overpriced designer candle pretty much whenever the mood strikes. The only way to avoid it is to only do the thing you already did. But that’s boring and not why you started. 🚀

Time for a rewatch?

Oh hey there

Are you ever stuck in traffic and you realize you’re surrounded by people, so many people, any of whom could do anything at any time and probably at least a couple of whom are living the last few days of their life, and also things like cars and buildings that could fall or crash right into you, and you suddenly realize your life is this unbelievably tenuous and extended-warrantee-free thing,, like a quart of milk has a more definitive expiration date, and in that instant you realize you’re so lucky you got to see what you saw and taste what you tasted and kiss who you kissed and you’re not done, if you have a say in the matter, you’ve got a real long to-do list and entire unexpressed worlds inside you and so much music you want to listen to and you really do not want to waste another second, or at least, to be more realistic, you want to waste a proportionally smaller number of seconds, because you are the sole guardian of the unknown sum total of your seconds? 

Anyway,
